➜Philippines may secure China's COVID-19 vaccine by Q1 next year: Sputnik
http://www.sohu.com/a/437010235_162758	29504
<p><img src="http://p9.itc.cn/q_70/images03/20201208/aa292507692149988dbe2ccdccf04272.jpeg" /></p>
<p>Screenshot shows the Sputnik news report on Dec. 2, 2020.</p>
<p>Philippines vaccine czar Carlito Galvez, Jr. said the Philippines may receive COVID-19 vaccines from China and Russia in the first quarter of 2021, Russian news agency Sputnik reported on Dec. 2.</p>
<p>According to a news report published by CNN Philippines on Dec. 2, the Philippines is likely to receive the COVID-19 vaccine from Chinese pharmaceutical company Sinovac Biotech and Russia's COVID-19 vaccine named "Sputnik V" as early as the first quarter next year.</p>
<p>Sinovac will have clinical trials in the Philippines in December or early January, Galvez said.</p>
<p>If the Philippine government concludes the agreement with Sinovac in December, the Chinese pharmaceutical manufacturer will need 60 to 90 days to prepare and ship the vaccine to the Philippine. Galvez had previously claimed that the Philippines planned to purchase fifty million COVID-19 vaccine doses from China.</p>
<p>The Philippine government would purchase COVID-19 vaccines from four companies including China's Sinovac, Philippine presidential spokesperson Harry Roque said on Dec. 1.</p>
<p>It was previously reported that the Philippines planned to vaccinate up to 60 million people of its 110 million population to achieve a herd immunity against COVID-19. The vaccination would cost the Philippine government about 1.5 billion U.S. dollars.</p>
<p>Find the original news report at http://sputniknews.cn/covid-2019/202012021032639763/</p>
<p>[责任编辑: SRQ ] </p>
